This paper uses methods from natural language processing (NLP) to analyze consumer activity patterns, specifically supermarket purchases. It applies a topic modeling approach to extract high-level concepts from product co-occurrence data. This methodology is commonly used in the NLP subfield of computational linguistics (cs.CL) and information retrieval (cs.IR). Additionally, the paper discusses the coherence and comprehensibility of the extracted topics, which are important considerations in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG). The paper also touches on the idea of tailoring conceptual knowledge to support action, which is relevant to the subfield of social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper's focus on consumer behavior and demographic characteristics could potentially fall under the subfield of cybernetics (cs.CY).
